Create a scatterplot of price vs carat and omit the top 1% of price and carat values.
remove_top_1_percent=subset(diamonds,diamonds$price<quantile(diamonds$price,0.9)||diamonds$carat<quantile(diamonds$carat,0.9))
ggplot(aes(y=price,x=carat),data=remove_top_1_percent)+geom_point()

Create a scatterplot of price vs. volume (x * y * z).
diamonds$vol=diamonds$x*diamonds$y*diamonds$z
ggplot(aes(x=vol,y=price),data=diamonds)+geom_point()

Line plot of Hours worked by countries where we have most of the data ```

library("ggplot2")
ggplot(aes(x=Year,y=Hours_Worked,group=Country,color=Country),data=work_hours_required)+geom_line()+geom_point()+ylim(25,45)

Facet wrap for each country to help understand distribution better France and Japan Spani Norway Finland   work hours have dropped dramatically .In Australia,Canada,Iceland,Italy,UnitedStates the rate of drop is not very significant its a flat line 
ggplot(aes(x=Year,y=Hours_Worked,group=Country),data=work_hours_required)+geom_line(color='blue')+facet_wrap(~Country)

ggplot(aes(x=Country,y=Hours_Worked),data=work_hours_required)+geom_boxplot()

No suprises here Japan has the highest work hours Norway Sweden and France lead the least
